00:00:26.370 --> 00:00:32.330
PROFESSOR: So I think we have
a bit of background in mind.

00:00:32.330 --> 00:00:37.570
So now I'm going to summarize
this discussion, and start

00:00:37.570 --> 00:00:41.580
asking about how do we go about
answering some of the

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:45.450
questions that have
come about?

00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:51.910
So at the end of last lecture,
we were left with our S-shaped

00:00:51.910 --> 00:00:54.560
curve, and saying that whether
or not there would be a

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:58.190
poverty trap was really
dependent on the shape of the

00:00:58.190 --> 00:01:01.910
curve that relates income today
to income tomorrow.

00:01:01.910 --> 00:01:05.340
And we gave sent out examples
where it could go one way or

00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:08.400
the other, or it could be that
its S shape, it could be that

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:11.160
it's increasing but
inverted L-shape.

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:14.220
And then one of you asked
the question,

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:16.860
well, how do we know?

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:19.830
How do we even get about--

00:01:19.830 --> 00:01:23.560
how do we get to know the
shape of the curve?

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:26.440
This is not a question that
is going to be solved

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:27.280
theoretically.

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:30.310
The debate we just had a moment
ago suggested it won't

00:01:30.310 --> 00:01:32.680
be solved theoretically.

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:36.760
Because, for example, take the
question of whether if I give

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:40.930
you a bed net for free today,
you're less likely to buy the

00:01:40.930 --> 00:01:42.190
next one tomorrow.

00:01:42.190 --> 00:01:45.350
It depends on whether the
entitlement effect is more

00:01:45.350 --> 00:01:47.660
important than the
loaning effect.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:48.720
And how will I know that?

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:52.200
There is no way for me
to know it without

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:54.160
looking at the data.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:58.500
And the question is, what's a
good way to look at the data?

00:01:58.500 --> 00:02:02.410
And today, we're going to look
at one such way, which is a

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:06.230
way which is increasingly often
used by development

00:02:06.230 --> 00:02:09.370
economists, by policy makers,
and which is the main approach

00:02:09.370 --> 00:02:13.290
that we are using in the Poverty
Action Lab, which is

00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:16.390
the idea of on randomized
evaluation.

00:02:16.390 --> 00:02:18.690
So we'll start with our
malaria example.

00:02:18.690 --> 00:02:21.550
I'm going to use the malaria
example, because we had the

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:23.410
debate, so we know the question
we're asking.

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:25.580
I'm going to use that
as our example.

00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:29.080
But, of course, the point I'm
making now are important

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:32.200
methodological points as well.

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:35.560
So what are we talking about?

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:38.230
We're talking about a pretty
important thing.

00:02:38.230 --> 00:02:42.700
Almost 900,000 people die of
malaria every year, give and

00:02:42.700 --> 00:02:46.370
take, most of them in Africa,
most of them under five.

00:02:46.370 --> 00:02:48.240
That's the biggest cause
of under-five

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:50.780
mortality in the world.

00:02:50.780 --> 00:02:54.730
Incidentally, you want to take
every single statistic with a

00:02:54.730 --> 00:02:58.080
big pinch of salt, because it's
not that all the malaria

00:02:58.080 --> 00:02:59.750
cases are recorded--

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:05.000
a lot of people who are not
really diagnosed of malaria

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.040
and are told to be dead of
malaria, so it could be a

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:09.930
gross overestimate or a
gross underestimate.

00:03:09.930 --> 00:03:12.042
But I think it's fair to say
it's a lot of people, one way

00:03:12.042 --> 00:03:13.292
or the other.

00:03:15.210 --> 00:03:19.250
As we discussed, malaria is
transmitted by mosquitoes who

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:22.280
carry the parasite from an
infected person to an

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:25.810
uninfected person,
mainly at dusk.

00:03:25.810 --> 00:03:31.130
So sleeping under a bed net,
particularly a bed net which

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:36.550
has insecticide woven into the
fiber of the bed net is an

00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:39.490
effective way to prevent
mosquito bites, and therefore

00:03:39.490 --> 00:03:43.150
to prevent the transmission
of malaria.

00:03:45.870 --> 00:03:51.450
And one thing that no one said,
which was important, is

00:03:51.450 --> 00:03:56.660
that there is two effects of
sleeping under a bed net.

00:03:56.660 --> 00:03:59.410
If you already don't have
malaria, you're less likely to

00:03:59.410 --> 00:04:03.600
catch it, because the mosquitoes
can't bite you.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:06.690
So this is a direct benefit
that benefits you.

00:04:06.690 --> 00:04:10.650
So when making the decision to
buy or not buy a bed net when

00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:14.510
making the decision to use the
bed net or not to use it, you

00:04:14.510 --> 00:04:18.920
are going to take this direct
benefit into account, right?

00:04:18.920 --> 00:04:21.529
But then there is another
benefit which is the

00:04:21.529 --> 00:04:24.810
externality, which is an
indirect effect, which is, if

00:04:24.810 --> 00:04:27.880
you already have malaria,
someone else is less likely to

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:29.605
get it because they don't
first bite you

00:04:29.605 --> 00:04:31.310
and then bite them.

00:04:31.310 --> 00:04:35.480
And this benefit, unless
you're an incredibly

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:38.520
socially-minded person, is a
benefit you don't take into

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:40.420
account when buying
your bed net.

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:41.300
Because you don't care.

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:41.660
It's not you.

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:42.830
It's someone else.

00:04:42.830 --> 00:04:48.810
But as society, we are trying to
maybe adjust the individual

00:04:48.810 --> 00:04:52.350
behavior to the social
benefit.

00:04:52.350 --> 00:04:55.180
There's one more thing which is
important for us to keep in

00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:58.600
mind, which is this externality
is not linear.

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:00.830
So it could be that the
externality is linear, which

00:05:00.830 --> 00:05:06.460
is one more person who sleeps
under a bed net, say half a

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:08.410
fewer percent is infected.

00:05:08.410 --> 00:05:10.870
So it could be like the more
bed nets you have, the less

00:05:10.870 --> 00:05:14.010
malaria you have, but in
a disproportional way.

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:16.736
But it turns out that it's
not proportional.

00:05:16.736 --> 00:05:22.050
The reason why it's not
proportionally is because once

00:05:22.050 --> 00:05:25.290
about half the population sleeps
under the bed net, you

00:05:25.290 --> 00:05:29.050
have something called hard
immunity, which is that the

00:05:29.050 --> 00:05:33.280
mosquitoes don't have time to
bite someone else before

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:37.140
either the mosquito or
the parasite dies.

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:42.450
So if you manage to cover about
half of your population,

00:05:42.450 --> 00:05:45.710
you don't even need to
carry the other half.

00:05:45.710 --> 00:05:48.020
I mean, it's better,
but they already

00:05:48.020 --> 00:05:50.300
benefit almost as much.

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:55.320
So the externality benefits are
like this, if you want.

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:58.220
They're like, first they're
linear, and then at some

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:00.770
point, they have a big jump in
the externality benefits.

00:06:00.770 --> 00:06:06.560
And then again, going from
80% to 85%, maybe less.

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:13.230
So that means that this would
need to be reminding you of

00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:16.920
the S-shaped thing, which is
there will be a distinct

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:23.100
advantage in terms of cost per
malaria averted, the benefit

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:28.380
of going from a coverage of 25%
to 30% of the population

00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:31.720
are going to be lower than the
benefit of going, say, from

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:33.950
45% to 50%.

00:06:33.950 --> 00:06:36.540
Because when you go from 45%
to 50%, you're in the zone

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:40.360
where every extra bed net is
really helping a huge deal.

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:41.990
So that is going to
be relevant when

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:43.240
we do the cost benefit.

00:06:45.580 --> 00:06:46.650
So that's the case
for bed nets.

00:06:46.650 --> 00:06:51.380
So now, if we were traditional
economists, we would make a

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:55.140
traditional economic argument,
which is to say, there is an

00:06:55.140 --> 00:06:56.570
externality.

00:06:56.570 --> 00:06:59.920
Whenever there is an
externality, we want to try to

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:06.460
do use prices or taxes to align
the private incentive

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:08.330
with the public incentive.

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:11.170
That's why, for example,
we would like to have a

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:14.440
congestion charge in London, or
we have a congestion charge

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:18.080
in London to make it expensive
to drive your car in London,

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:20.530
in the center of London, because
when you drive your

00:07:20.530 --> 00:07:22.535
car in the center of London,
that's a pain

00:07:22.535 --> 00:07:23.785
for everybody else.

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:32.120
That could be one of the reasons
why we have taxes on

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:36.710
cigarettes, that smokers impose
an externality on the

00:07:36.710 --> 00:07:40.900
rest of the people, here both
because of secondhand smoking,

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:43.110
and because they
get sick a lot.

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:45.250
So you would think that society
has a right to impose

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:50.750
a tax on them to try and
discourage them from smoking.

00:07:50.750 --> 00:07:56.550
So by using prices and taxes is
where you can try and align

00:07:56.550 --> 00:07:59.260
the private incentive to
the social benefit.

00:07:59.260 --> 00:07:59.610
Yes?

00:07:59.610 --> 00:08:02.005
AUDIENCE: Can you do community
incentives, like you tell the

00:08:02.005 --> 00:08:04.879
community if everyone uses their
bed nets as bed nets,

00:08:04.879 --> 00:08:07.760
you'll give the community a
certain number of fishing nets

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:10.168
so that people will encourage
or force other

00:08:10.168 --> 00:08:11.500
people to use bed nets?

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:12.150
ESTHER DUFLO: Right.

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:16.860
So one way is the prices, but
another way could be to have

00:08:16.860 --> 00:08:18.110
community incentives.

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:23.670
Indonesia has a program where
they are trying to give

00:08:23.670 --> 00:08:30.170
community incentive so if, say
90% percent of the community

00:08:30.170 --> 00:08:35.000
is immunized, and x percent to
the community is in school,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.770
then they get some amount of
money to build a road, or an

00:08:38.770 --> 00:08:41.140
irrigation project, or
something like that.

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:41.420
AUDIENCE: I'm just curious.

00:08:41.420 --> 00:08:44.930
How much is given in foreign
aid to fight malaria?

00:08:44.930 --> 00:08:46.800
ESTHER DUFLO: That's an
excellent-- how much is given

00:08:46.800 --> 00:08:47.870
in foreign aid to
fight malaria.

00:08:47.870 --> 00:08:51.990
It's an excellent question, the
answer to which I don't

00:08:51.990 --> 00:08:54.728
know off the top of my head,
but it's findable.

00:08:54.728 --> 00:08:57.540
AUDIENCE: Because I was going
to ask if the cost of

00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:01.112
providing a country with bed
nets is significantly less

00:09:01.112 --> 00:09:04.840
than the cost of giving
[INAUDIBLE] money to fight

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:08.816
malaria, then I don't even
see why it's as big of a

00:09:08.816 --> 00:09:10.307
debate as it is.

00:09:10.307 --> 00:09:12.626
Clearly, they should figure out
what's the most effective

00:09:12.626 --> 00:09:16.768
way to distribute the bed nets,
make sure [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:16.768 --> 00:09:20.247
But the option of not giving
them just wouldn't make as

00:09:20.247 --> 00:09:22.235
much sense, in terms of
cost [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:25.250 --> 00:09:26.120
ESTHER DUFLO: Oh, I see.

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:28.240
So providing bed nets
would be part of the

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:29.490
budget of fighting malaria.

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:34.450
So your question is that, if
we're already spending so much

00:09:34.450 --> 00:09:37.380
money on medicine against
malaria, we would really be

00:09:37.380 --> 00:09:39.440
willing to spend a lot
of money on bed nets.

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:40.660
You're exactly right.

00:09:40.660 --> 00:09:46.050
And I don't think the debate
is that we want to try and

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:47.660
save money on the bed nets.

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:51.770
I think the debate is always
about what's the best way to

00:09:51.770 --> 00:09:54.080
get the money out.

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:57.420
So this would argue, so the
fact that the private

00:09:57.420 --> 00:10:01.350
incentive to get your bed net
is low, would argue for

00:10:01.350 --> 00:10:08.530
subsidizing the bed net, but
only if the private incentives

00:10:08.530 --> 00:10:11.760
are not large enough that people
are already not buying

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:12.860
your bed net.

00:10:12.860 --> 00:10:16.330
So suppose, for example, that
people hated being sick,

00:10:16.330 --> 00:10:19.700
which, presumably, they do.

00:10:19.700 --> 00:10:21.910
Then, they would get
the bed net anyway.

00:10:21.910 --> 00:10:24.770
You would not need to subsidize
the bed net.

00:10:24.770 --> 00:10:27.020
So there would not be an effect
of the price, because

00:10:27.020 --> 00:10:30.430
the demand would be very
high at any price.

00:10:30.430 --> 00:10:34.030
So the fact that there is
an externality justifies

00:10:34.030 --> 00:10:38.120
subsidizing, to the extent that
the private incentives

00:10:38.120 --> 00:10:44.890
are too small for people to want
to get them themselves.

00:10:44.890 --> 00:10:50.060
Another traditional economics
argument would be the learning

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:53.960
argument that was made earlier,
which is that trying

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:58.300
your bed net once might give you
the experience of it, and

00:10:58.300 --> 00:11:01.260
once you knew how it works,
and you know how well it

00:11:01.260 --> 00:11:06.530
protects your children, you
might be more likely to get

00:11:06.530 --> 00:11:07.950
the next one.

00:11:07.950 --> 00:11:10.970
And then there is an argument
that mixes the two, which is

00:11:10.970 --> 00:11:14.820
another externality argument,
which is, if try a bed net,

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:17.520
and I realize that it protects
my children and it's really

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:21.030
not so unpleasant, then maybe my
neighbors will also see my

00:11:21.030 --> 00:11:22.730
bed net, and say, oh,
isn't this cool.

00:11:22.730 --> 00:11:24.350
We want also a bed net.

00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:27.060
So there is an externality in
my trying, potentially.

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:28.050
Yeah?

00:11:28.050 --> 00:11:30.772
AUDIENCE: But if you were
charged for bed nets and the

00:11:30.772 --> 00:11:34.485
borrower that could, again, come
in to have the bed nets

00:11:34.485 --> 00:11:35.735
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:11:42.910 --> 00:11:43.950
ESTHER DUFLO: Yes.

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:49.200
So eventually, since there are
those contingent benefits,

00:11:49.200 --> 00:11:52.470
someone who is very rational
might feel, already more than

00:11:52.470 --> 00:11:54.620
50% bed nets in this
community.

00:11:54.620 --> 00:11:56.780
I don't need to get
the next one.

00:11:56.780 --> 00:12:00.520
So the private incentives
diminish as the coverage

00:12:00.520 --> 00:12:05.260
increases, which makes it more
necessary either to subsidize

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:10.510
it even more, or to tax people
if they don't get a bed net.

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:14.090
So this is an argument that
is made for immunization.

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:19.360
So in this country, immunization
is compulsory for

00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:20.990
a range of diseases.

00:12:20.990 --> 00:12:23.630
Except if you really don't want
to do it because you have

00:12:23.630 --> 00:12:29.940
some religious or whatever
reasons for not wanting to be

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:33.080
immunized, then you can say,
sorry, I refuse the

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:34.890
immunization.

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:44.600
And people worry that as
diseases such as polio, or

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:48.450
diphtheria, or pertussis, these
types of diseases become

00:12:48.450 --> 00:12:51.980
less frequent, people don't have
the fear of getting those

00:12:51.980 --> 00:12:54.750
diseases anymore, and they want
to free ride on the rest

00:12:54.750 --> 00:12:55.800
of the community.

00:12:55.800 --> 00:13:00.780
And that's, of course, bad,
because being 100% immunized

00:13:00.780 --> 00:13:03.440
ensures that the disease
goes away.

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:07.480
As soon as a few people
are not immunized,

00:13:07.480 --> 00:13:08.930
it could come back.

00:13:08.930 --> 00:13:13.820
And so there is this tension
between once almost everyone's

00:13:13.820 --> 00:13:15.670
immunized, your private
incentive to do

00:13:15.670 --> 00:13:17.080
it are almost zero.

00:13:17.080 --> 00:13:23.180
So you might need powerful
inducement to get to do it.

00:13:23.180 --> 00:13:26.080
So those are the traditional
economic arguments.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:27.620
These are your traditional
public finance--

00:13:27.620 --> 00:13:29.960
let's use the prices.

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:32.870
That indicates that we should
subsidize the bed nets.

00:13:32.870 --> 00:13:34.390
And by the way, there
is no reason to

00:13:34.390 --> 00:13:35.740
stop at zero in principle.

00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:39.480
We could pay people to use bed
nets, for that matter, if this

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:45.250
was the way to get the optimal
coverage in the community.

00:13:45.250 --> 00:13:46.228
Yeah?

00:13:46.228 --> 00:13:49.406
AUDIENCE: So one consideration
that comes to mind is if

00:13:49.406 --> 00:13:51.607
there's a segment of the
population that is really,

00:13:51.607 --> 00:13:54.378
really poor and cannot afford to
pay any amount for the bed

00:13:54.378 --> 00:13:56.110
nets, whether they're subsidized
or not, those

00:13:56.110 --> 00:13:58.830
people are also the least likely
to be able to pay for

00:13:58.830 --> 00:14:00.244
health care should
they get malaria.

00:14:00.244 --> 00:14:02.940
So they would have the greatest
risk for everyone

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:04.235
else and for themselves.

00:14:04.235 --> 00:14:06.760
So wouldn't you want to try to
provide free bed nets for that

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:10.320
set of people, no matter what?

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:13.450
ESTHER DUFLO: Right, so that's
another consideration that you

00:14:13.450 --> 00:14:17.730
might want to include, a
redistribution consideration,

00:14:17.730 --> 00:14:24.540
which you might feel that people
who are particularly

00:14:24.540 --> 00:14:27.435
poor might have a very high
private evaluation of the bed

00:14:27.435 --> 00:14:30.320
nets, but might be credit
constrained and not be able to

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:31.440
get the bed net.

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:33.880
And those are the same people
who will also not be able to

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:35.530
cure themselves of malaria.

00:14:35.530 --> 00:14:39.420
So here, that gives you
another argument for

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:42.580
subsidizing bed nets, which is
not an argument in terms of

00:14:42.580 --> 00:14:45.380
disease eradication, but
an argument in terms of

00:14:45.380 --> 00:14:48.560
redistribution between people.

00:14:48.560 --> 00:14:50.400
So those are traditional
arguments.

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:55.450
They are taken, say, by Jeff
Sachs, or by the WHO, and say,

00:14:55.450 --> 00:15:00.350
we should subsidize bed net
to a large extent, or

00:15:00.350 --> 00:15:03.870
potentially, up to giving
them away for free.

00:15:03.870 --> 00:15:08.210
And then we have the less
conventional economics, which

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:13.070
we discussed, which has the
argument that goes in the

00:15:13.070 --> 00:15:15.630
opposite direction, or the
psychological sunk cost

00:15:15.630 --> 00:15:19.410
effect, which is, you have to
pay for something to really

00:15:19.410 --> 00:15:21.780
appreciate its value.

00:15:21.780 --> 00:15:24.350
There is a selection effect
which is, if you give things

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:27.650
away for free, even people who
don't want it or who don't

00:15:27.650 --> 00:15:30.630
want it for its legitimate use
are going to come and get it.

00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:33.950
They're going to waste
a lot of bed nets.

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:37.190
And finally, the entitlement
effect, which counters the

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:39.390
learning effect, which is, once
you get something for

00:15:39.390 --> 00:15:44.160
free, then you expect to get
it for free in the future.

00:15:44.160 --> 00:15:47.960
And it might even have
contingent things, which is

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:51.400
you're not going to want to get
chlorine to purify your

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:54.690
water, unless someone
is giving it to you.

00:15:54.690 --> 00:15:59.380
You're not going to want to
send your kids to school

00:15:59.380 --> 00:16:03.750
unless they get a school meal,
other things like that, which

00:16:03.750 --> 00:16:06.210
find that you become
dependent.

00:16:06.210 --> 00:16:06.710
Yeah?

00:16:06.710 --> 00:16:07.710
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:16:07.710 --> 00:16:11.710
Couldn't you argue that it's not
sustainable, [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:11.710 --> 00:16:15.210
long-term policy and exit
strategies, because if you're

00:16:15.210 --> 00:16:16.210
[INAUDIBLE]

00:16:16.210 --> 00:16:19.710
subsidizing and giving away bed
nets, you might crowd out

00:16:19.710 --> 00:16:20.710
the private sector.

00:16:20.710 --> 00:16:25.460
And you won't [INAUDIBLE] your
desired outcome, which is for

00:16:25.460 --> 00:16:26.710
people to be using bed nets.

00:16:29.210 --> 00:16:31.840
ESTHER DUFLO: So in the
traditional public finance

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:35.140
argument, why would you
ever want to stop to

00:16:35.140 --> 00:16:37.154
subsidize the bed net?

00:16:37.154 --> 00:16:38.480
AUDIENCE: Want to
not subsidize--

00:16:38.480 --> 00:16:38.650
ESTHER DUFLO: Yeah.

00:16:38.650 --> 00:16:43.105
Why would you ever want to stop,
given those arguments?

00:16:43.105 --> 00:16:44.570
AUDIENCE: To create a market?

00:16:44.570 --> 00:16:45.750
ESTHER DUFLO: Why would you?

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:49.360
Take, for example, immunization
in the US.

00:16:49.360 --> 00:16:51.830
Immunization is subsidized
and compulsory.

00:16:51.830 --> 00:16:56.450
Is there any plan to make
immunization not subsidized or

00:16:56.450 --> 00:16:57.225
compulsory?

00:16:57.225 --> 00:16:57.690
AUDIENCE: That's true.

00:16:57.690 --> 00:16:59.290
ESTHER DUFLO: There's
no such plan.

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:02.270
This kind of argument would
tell you that you want to

00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:07.510
subsidize forever, because the
private gains and the social

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:10.970
gains are not aligned for a
fundamental reason, which is

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:13.670
my being protected by a bed net
protects you as well, and

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:15.660
that's never going to change.

00:17:15.660 --> 00:17:17.780
So in that sense, you're
not doing a policy

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:18.579
for the short run.

00:17:18.579 --> 00:17:21.450
You're doing this policy
for the long run.

00:17:21.450 --> 00:17:25.420
Now, again, we had this
discussion earlier, which is

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:28.079
the questions of who provides
the bed net, whether they can

00:17:28.079 --> 00:17:30.630
be provided locally instead
of imported, are all very

00:17:30.630 --> 00:17:33.770
legitimate questions, but in a
sense, unrelated to the price

00:17:33.770 --> 00:17:36.040
you're going to charge.

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:38.360
So that's an excellent question,
because it comes

00:17:38.360 --> 00:17:40.280
back all the time, which
is to say, oh, but

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:41.720
don't we want to exit?

00:17:41.720 --> 00:17:44.380
Just think, whenever you want to
ask yourself this question

00:17:44.380 --> 00:17:46.680
about sustainability,
ask yourself, why

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:47.560
would I want to exit?

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:48.520
Maybe I don't.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:53.890
Maybe it is actually socially
efficient to subsidize

00:17:53.890 --> 00:17:59.180
something for eternity, because
as Ben was saying, you

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:06.020
save on the cost of curing
people from malaria.

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:11.100
So the argument that goes
against giving people for free

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:14.760
are these arguments that giving
bed nets for free or

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:18.240
even subsidizing them is
counterproductive, in terms of

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:19.940
distributing bed nets.

00:18:19.940 --> 00:18:22.860
It's counterproductive because
of the sunk cost effect,

00:18:22.860 --> 00:18:25.140
because of the selection
effect, or because this

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:29.460
entitlement effect that then
nobody is ever going to want

00:18:29.460 --> 00:18:34.004
to buy anything, either a bed
net or something else.

00:18:34.004 --> 00:18:40.970
And these elements are
very reasonable.

00:18:40.970 --> 00:18:43.300
Both sides of the arguments
are, in principle, very

00:18:43.300 --> 00:18:44.480
reasonable.

00:18:44.480 --> 00:18:45.530
And they might apply here.

00:18:45.530 --> 00:18:47.250
We just don't know.

00:18:47.250 --> 00:18:50.140
It's a very heated
policy debate.

00:18:50.140 --> 00:18:54.520
The laws that are involved in
bed nets are nowhere near the

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:56.900
laws that are involved in oil or
anything, but it's still a

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:59.640
fair amount of dollars,
so people like those.

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:02.270
So there is a lot of debate.

00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:06.650
So Jeff Sachs of the WHO relies
on the convention

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:08.330
economics argument to say
you should give the

00:19:08.330 --> 00:19:10.080
bed nets for free.

00:19:10.080 --> 00:19:12.900
Then you have people like Bill
Easterly or Dambisa Moyo, who

00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:18.820
are making the argument based
on this entitlement effect,

00:19:18.820 --> 00:19:24.690
sunk cost effect, the
development of market, to say

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:26.540
we shouldn't give
them for free.

00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:29.790
And both arguments tell you,
in a sense, we know the

00:19:29.790 --> 00:19:33.960
economics, and the answer
is obvious.

00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:36.360
There is no reason
to find out.

00:19:36.360 --> 00:19:41.070
And I think there is value in
both type of arguments that

00:19:41.070 --> 00:19:41.670
they are making.

00:19:41.670 --> 00:19:44.380
But there is no value
in this last one.

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:47.360
Because since there is value
in both arguments, we don't

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:49.010
know the answer.

00:19:49.010 --> 00:19:53.530
The answer depends on the
balance of how they turn out

00:19:53.530 --> 00:19:55.505
in the specific application
of bed nets.

00:19:58.070 --> 00:20:00.810
So the true question we want to
ask is the extent to which

00:20:00.810 --> 00:20:03.770
we should subsidize bed nets.

00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:06.080
And for that, what do
we need to know?

00:20:06.080 --> 00:20:09.480
Well, first we need to know
whether or not bed nets are

00:20:09.480 --> 00:20:11.490
really price elastic.

00:20:11.490 --> 00:20:15.230
So are we losing a lot of
coverage in terms of people

00:20:15.230 --> 00:20:20.380
acquiring bed nets, if we start
selling them instead of

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:22.810
giving them for free.

00:20:22.810 --> 00:20:24.620
Second question we need
to ask is the

00:20:24.620 --> 00:20:27.120
immediate effect on use.

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:31.087
So is it the case that people
who pay for bed nets are more

00:20:31.087 --> 00:20:34.920
likely to use it than people
who got it for free?

00:20:34.920 --> 00:20:37.570
Third question is the
longer-term effect.

00:20:37.570 --> 00:20:39.610
Will it wreck markets?

00:20:39.610 --> 00:20:43.050
And for that, that's the
entitlement effect.

00:20:43.050 --> 00:20:46.680
For people who get it for free,
in the future, are they

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:49.930
more or less likely
to buy one?

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:53.560
And for people who are around
them in the community--

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:55.870
this is something we didn't
discuss much, but if I'm

00:20:55.870 --> 00:20:58.410
around you in the community,
and I see you having a free

00:20:58.410 --> 00:21:02.210
bed net, it could affect
me in one of two ways.

00:21:02.210 --> 00:21:06.280
I could say, first of all,
oh, she has a bed net.

00:21:06.280 --> 00:21:07.170
That's really nice.

00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:08.160
Her kids are doing well.

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:10.160
I'm going to get one too.

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:12.070
I could say, oh, she
got a free bed net.

00:21:12.070 --> 00:21:13.510
Let me wait until I get--

00:21:13.510 --> 00:21:15.730
I was going to buy a bed net,
but now I'm going to wait

00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:17.550
until I get a free bed net.

00:21:17.550 --> 00:21:20.170
And so I wasn't going to sell
a bed net, and now I'm going

00:21:20.170 --> 00:21:21.740
to have give it for free.

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:24.190
So that's wasted money.

00:21:24.190 --> 00:21:27.380
So again, we don't know
which way it cuts.

00:21:27.380 --> 00:21:30.190
We have to look in practice.

00:21:30.190 --> 00:21:32.650
And those questions are pretty
well-defined questions.

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:34.930
They are empirical questions
we could principally

00:21:34.930 --> 00:21:37.280
bring an answer to.

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:39.070
There are a lot of anecdotes.

00:21:39.070 --> 00:21:44.180
They are this one, which is bed
nets used as fishing nets.

00:21:44.180 --> 00:21:47.280
That's a picture that was in the
Malaria Journal, so it's

00:21:47.280 --> 00:21:51.470
all peer reviewed
and all that.

00:21:51.470 --> 00:21:55.670
So this is the Easterly Dambisa
Moyo argument, that

00:21:55.670 --> 00:21:59.300
you are going to see the used
as a fishing net, or wedding

00:21:59.300 --> 00:22:02.020
veils, or what have you.

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:05.880
And then this is the other
argument, of the other

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:09.750
anecdote of the bed net being
nicely hanged in the room, and

00:22:09.750 --> 00:22:12.570
the child, the healthy child
who slept in there

00:22:12.570 --> 00:22:13.500
under the bed net.

00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:15.910
So that's not too helpful.

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:19.350
So we want to go further
that the anecdote.

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:22.690
There are many anecdotes,
and they cut both ways.

00:22:28.700 --> 00:22:33.270
How do we go further
than the anecdote?

00:22:33.270 --> 00:22:37.065
So the first thing we could
do-- so suppose you

00:22:37.065 --> 00:22:38.680
were given this job.

00:22:38.680 --> 00:22:42.816
I tell you, find out for me
whether people who get their

00:22:42.816 --> 00:22:45.470
bed nets for free are more
likely to use it as fishing

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:49.830
nets or more likely to
use them as bed nets.

00:22:49.830 --> 00:22:53.670
And also, find out whether if I
distribute the bed nets for

00:22:53.670 --> 00:22:57.230
free, I distribute many more
of them or I distribute the

00:22:57.230 --> 00:22:58.100
same amount.

00:22:58.100 --> 00:23:03.280
What would your first
response to what you

00:23:03.280 --> 00:23:04.530
should go out and do?

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:08.130
AUDIENCE: Yeah?

00:23:08.130 --> 00:23:11.070
I would find two similar
communities, and then

00:23:11.070 --> 00:23:12.540
[INAUDIBLE]

00:23:12.540 --> 00:23:16.950
give bed nets would be one, and
maybe help someone start a

00:23:16.950 --> 00:23:20.070
small business of selling
bed nets in the other.

00:23:20.070 --> 00:23:22.370
ESTHER DUFLO: So you would take
two similar communities,

00:23:22.370 --> 00:23:27.870
and in once case, give bed
nets for free, and in one

00:23:27.870 --> 00:23:32.340
case, start to sell them,
maybe by finding a small

00:23:32.340 --> 00:23:35.010
business, or maybe importing
them to the village.

00:23:35.010 --> 00:23:37.320
What would be an even---

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:38.080
we'll go back to that.

00:23:38.080 --> 00:23:42.510
What would be an even easier,
even more immediate way to do

00:23:42.510 --> 00:23:47.190
it that we could think of to
start with, if we needed to do

00:23:47.190 --> 00:23:49.276
this quickly?

00:23:49.276 --> 00:23:49.748
Yes?

00:23:49.748 --> 00:23:50.456
AUDIENCE: Just look at the

00:23:50.456 --> 00:23:53.524
communities where it is already.

00:23:53.524 --> 00:23:53.996
ESTHER DUFLO: Right.

00:23:53.996 --> 00:23:56.270
You would look at a community
where this is already in

00:23:56.270 --> 00:23:59.090
place, and you would say, well,
in this community, the

00:23:59.090 --> 00:24:02.365
bed nets are given for free, and
in this community, the bed

00:24:02.365 --> 00:24:04.070
nets are sold.

00:24:04.070 --> 00:24:04.590
Let me try my thing.

00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:05.780
Yeah.

00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:07.800
In this community, the bed
nets are given for free.

00:24:07.800 --> 00:24:10.240
In this community, the
bed nets are sold.

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:13.960
First question, do I see more
bed nets where the bed nets

00:24:13.960 --> 00:24:16.230
are not given for free?

00:24:16.230 --> 00:24:20.140
Second question, do I see the
bed nets more likely to be

00:24:20.140 --> 00:24:22.790
used as fishing nets in
those communities?

00:24:22.790 --> 00:24:27.150
So that's, I think, what
most people would--

00:24:27.150 --> 00:24:31.260
that would be your
initial instinct.

00:24:31.260 --> 00:24:34.230
The problem you would have if
you did that, as opposed to--

00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:35.870
sorry, can you remind
of your name?

00:24:35.870 --> 00:24:36.820
AUDIENCE: [? Sif. ?]

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:36.960
ESTHER DUFLO: [? Sif. ?]

00:24:36.960 --> 00:24:39.160
The problem to do that, as
opposed to do what [? Sif ?]

00:24:39.160 --> 00:24:46.740
suggested, is to know why some
community happened to be the

00:24:46.740 --> 00:24:50.110
one that got them for free and
some community happened not to

00:24:50.110 --> 00:24:52.270
have the free distribution.

00:24:52.270 --> 00:24:55.540
So let's think of one reason
why there might be a free--

00:24:55.540 --> 00:24:59.190
if you were to start a free bed
net distribution program

00:24:59.190 --> 00:25:03.240
somewhere, where would
you start it?

00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:05.730
You have a country and you want
to start a free bed net

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:07.330
distribution, what
would you pick?

00:25:07.330 --> 00:25:07.610
Yes?

00:25:07.610 --> 00:25:08.951
AUDIENCE: If there was
a particularly bad

00:25:08.951 --> 00:25:10.740
increase, or something.

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:11.140
ESTHER DUFLO: Right.

00:25:11.140 --> 00:25:14.010
You would try to pick a place
where there is a lot of

00:25:14.010 --> 00:25:17.030
malaria, presumably, or
maybe a place where

00:25:17.030 --> 00:25:19.770
people are very poor.

00:25:19.770 --> 00:25:25.580
So let's work with the example
where you would pick, to start

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:28.080
your free bed net distribution,
the region where

00:25:28.080 --> 00:25:29.790
there is a lot of malaria.

00:25:29.790 --> 00:25:31.040
It would make sense.

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:36.720
So if that's the case that free
bed nets are distributed

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:41.400
where malaria is a huge problem,
then in these places,

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:45.660
even if they had to pay for the
bed net, they might have

00:25:45.660 --> 00:25:48.780
purchased them more willingly
than in places where malaria

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:51.490
is not such a big
problem anyway.

00:25:51.490 --> 00:25:54.180
Because the private benefits of
having a bed net is higher

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:56.110
in those [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:56.110 --> 00:25:59.810
So this is what we call the
counter-factual, which is what

00:25:59.810 --> 00:26:03.190
would have happened in the place
where the bed net got

00:26:03.190 --> 00:26:08.280
distributed for free if they
had actually been sold.

00:26:08.280 --> 00:26:11.010
So let's look at it in the
form of a simple graph.

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:13.100
So suppose we have two--

00:26:13.100 --> 00:26:15.800
we are going to do the argument
for purchase, and the

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:19.500
same kind of discussion
we could have for use.

00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:21.970
So suppose we have two regions,
a high-malaria region

00:26:21.970 --> 00:26:24.040
and a low-malaria region.

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:31.000
And suppose that God told us
this is how many people would

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:34.750
buy a bed net, the fraction of
people who would buy a bed net

00:26:34.750 --> 00:26:39.380
in the high-malaria region and
the low-malaria region, if the

00:26:39.380 --> 00:26:42.130
bed net was not subsidized.

00:26:42.130 --> 00:26:48.570
And this dot is higher, because
since malaria is more

00:26:48.570 --> 00:26:51.620
of a problems, people are more
willing to buy bed nets.

00:26:51.620 --> 00:26:53.100
OK?

00:26:53.100 --> 00:26:57.500
So that's what we would have
if bed nets were expensive.

00:26:57.500 --> 00:27:03.550
And if bed nets were free,
we would have those ones.

00:27:03.550 --> 00:27:06.310
So compared to the previous
dots, they are higher.

00:27:06.310 --> 00:27:07.730
Why are they higher
in both regions?

00:27:11.480 --> 00:27:12.550
AUDIENCE: It's because
they're free.

00:27:12.550 --> 00:27:14.270
ESTHER DUFLO: Because they're
free, so you're more likely to

00:27:14.270 --> 00:27:16.285
get something free than
to have to pay for it.

00:27:18.910 --> 00:27:21.230
But they are still higher in
the high-malaria region,

00:27:21.230 --> 00:27:24.270
because why would you get a
bed net in a region where

00:27:24.270 --> 00:27:25.430
malaria is not a problem?

00:27:25.430 --> 00:27:26.880
You really don't need it.

00:27:26.880 --> 00:27:29.080
If you don't have a fishing
boat, you don't need a fishing

00:27:29.080 --> 00:27:30.260
net either.

00:27:30.260 --> 00:27:33.695
So they are still higher in a
high-malaria region then in a

00:27:33.695 --> 00:27:36.220
low-malaria region when
bed nets are free.

00:27:36.220 --> 00:27:40.100
So this is what God would
have given you.

00:27:40.100 --> 00:27:43.690
But sadly, God didn't
give you that.

00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:49.680
