00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:02.320
the problem is.

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:07.100
So we have a problem, which is
that we observe the low prices

00:41:07.100 --> 00:41:10.870
in places where the need is
high, and high prices in the

00:41:10.870 --> 00:41:12.710
regions where they need
is low, so that

00:41:12.710 --> 00:41:14.670
leads to this bias.

00:41:14.670 --> 00:41:18.180
And the solution is exactly what
you suggested, which is,

00:41:18.180 --> 00:41:21.680
let's have variation in prices
in regions where

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:23.090
the need is the same.

00:41:23.090 --> 00:41:24.584
Yes?

00:41:24.584 --> 00:41:27.572
AUDIENCE: So on the x-axis, are
you exactly correlating

00:41:27.572 --> 00:41:32.440
the price of the bed nets with
the incidence of malaria, or--

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:36.040
ESTHER DUFLO: So what I'm
assuming, I'm telling you this

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:37.110
doesn't have to be true.

00:41:37.110 --> 00:41:39.600
And the problem is we'll never
know, because we won't observe

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:41.060
both in the real world.

00:41:41.060 --> 00:41:44.910
But I'm telling you this happens
to be like that in

00:41:44.910 --> 00:41:47.590
this particular fictional world
that I constructed,

00:41:47.590 --> 00:41:50.177
where this was like that.

00:41:50.177 --> 00:41:52.278
AUDIENCE: But if you go along
the x-axis to the right, you

00:41:52.278 --> 00:41:54.847
mean that bed nets get more
expensive and malaria

00:41:54.847 --> 00:41:56.250
incidence goes up?

00:41:56.250 --> 00:41:57.600
ESTHER DUFLO: Goes down.

00:41:57.600 --> 00:41:58.610
AUDIENCE: I'm sorry,
goes down?

00:41:58.610 --> 00:41:59.120
ESTHER DUFLO: Exactly.

00:41:59.120 --> 00:42:00.060
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:42:00.060 --> 00:42:01.310
ESTHER DUFLO: I constructed
it that way.

00:42:04.300 --> 00:42:07.220
You could construct the opposite
example, and you

00:42:07.220 --> 00:42:10.920
could make up a story where the
richer regions have more

00:42:10.920 --> 00:42:14.470
political power, and they
also have less malaria.

00:42:14.470 --> 00:42:17.780
So the richer region will get
the free bed nets, and they

00:42:17.780 --> 00:42:19.560
will also have less malaria.

00:42:19.560 --> 00:42:23.550
In that case, where would the
observed compared to the true

00:42:23.550 --> 00:42:27.580
elasticity, where would the red
dot be, if, in fact, the

00:42:27.580 --> 00:42:28.890
correlation was the other way?

00:42:33.840 --> 00:42:34.830
AUDIENCE: They would
go the other way?

00:42:34.830 --> 00:42:36.070
ESTHER DUFLO: They would
go the other way.

00:42:36.070 --> 00:42:44.020
So the red dot would be above,
because the bed nets are more

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:46.660
expensive where they
are more needed.

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:50.140
And your question brings in an
essential question, which is,

00:42:50.140 --> 00:42:52.880
sadly, we can't know.

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:55.510
We can know some stuff, which
is we can, for example,

00:42:55.510 --> 00:42:57.360
measure malaria prevalence.

00:42:57.360 --> 00:43:04.050
But we never observe the
counter-factual.

00:43:04.050 --> 00:43:07.890
So either we observe the demand,
where the price is

00:43:07.890 --> 00:43:14.010
high, in the places where it's
high, or we observe the demand

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:16.570
where the price is low in the
places where it's low.

00:43:16.570 --> 00:43:20.950
And we never get to see the
demand where the price is low

00:43:20.950 --> 00:43:22.730
in the places where it's high.

00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:24.840
That's the missing data point.

00:43:24.840 --> 00:43:27.270
That's why this is what
we are missing.

00:43:27.270 --> 00:43:30.000
In other words, we don't see
those yellow points.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:34.410
We don't see what the demand
would have been in a zero

00:43:34.410 --> 00:43:38.440
price region if the price, in
fact, had been 10, 20, 30.

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:39.690
We just don't know.

00:43:43.980 --> 00:43:48.840
So the solution is what you
suggested, which is to say,

00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:52.950
why don't we take one region and
try to vary the prices in

00:43:52.950 --> 00:43:53.520
those regions?

00:43:53.520 --> 00:43:56.385
Or in fact, we could take two
regions, a high-malaria region

00:43:56.385 --> 00:43:59.190
and a low-malaria region,
and vary the prices

00:43:59.190 --> 00:44:01.080
in those two regions.

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:04.070
And this is where the word
experiment comes up.

00:44:04.070 --> 00:44:07.160
This is where the experiment is,
which is the way you would

00:44:07.160 --> 00:44:11.910
do it to be completely sure that
there is no difference

00:44:11.910 --> 00:44:15.690
between the places or the people
which got the bed net

00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:18.780
for free, and the places or
people which had to pay for

00:44:18.780 --> 00:44:23.385
it, is you would randomly assign
the price of the bed

00:44:23.385 --> 00:44:27.470
net to different regions or
two different people.

00:44:27.470 --> 00:44:32.200
So this is what is done, for
example, in medicine when you

00:44:32.200 --> 00:44:34.100
want when you want
to find out the

00:44:34.100 --> 00:44:37.010
effectiveness of a new drug.

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:41.020
You don't give the new drug to
people who need it the most.

00:44:41.020 --> 00:44:42.620
Otherwise, you would
find that the drug

00:44:42.620 --> 00:44:44.810
killed a lot of people.

00:44:44.810 --> 00:44:48.800
You take some part of people
who need the drug, and you

00:44:48.800 --> 00:44:51.680
randomly assign some people to
take the drug and some people

00:44:51.680 --> 00:44:53.090
to get the placebo.

00:44:53.090 --> 00:44:55.810
You might also take a sample
of people who need the drug

00:44:55.810 --> 00:45:00.020
less, and randomly assign the
drug within them, to find out

00:45:00.020 --> 00:45:02.240
side effect if you
misprescribe.

00:45:02.240 --> 00:45:05.530
But you wouldn't give the drug
to people who need it, and not

00:45:05.530 --> 00:45:08.085
the drug to people who don't
need it, otherwise all of the

00:45:08.085 --> 00:45:10.790
drugs would be sure to
kill a lot of people.

00:45:10.790 --> 00:45:17.380
So most evaluation of social
policy is trying to estimate

00:45:17.380 --> 00:45:23.030
the effect of policies by
doing these kind of

00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:26.530
comparisons, this point
to this point.

00:45:26.530 --> 00:45:30.215
And that creates this
bias situation.

00:45:32.720 --> 00:45:36.130
And in fact, you can try and
make more progress on this

00:45:36.130 --> 00:45:40.620
question by creating experiments
where you fix the

00:45:40.620 --> 00:45:43.570
region, or you fix the
environment, and you randomly

00:45:43.570 --> 00:45:45.000
assign the prices.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:47.740
The randomization ensures
that there is nothing

00:45:47.740 --> 00:45:51.450
systematically different between
the people who got the

00:45:51.450 --> 00:45:54.130
free bed net and people
who didn't get it.

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:56.970
In other words, there is no--

00:45:56.970 --> 00:46:01.790
if we go back to this graph, for
example, the places that

00:46:01.790 --> 00:46:04.900
got the free bed net and the
places that had to pay for the

00:46:04.900 --> 00:46:08.170
bed net, if they had gotten it
for free, they would be at the

00:46:08.170 --> 00:46:09.460
same level.

00:46:09.460 --> 00:46:11.300
And if they had pay
for it, they would

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:12.530
be at the same level.

00:46:12.530 --> 00:46:14.990
There is now no difference
between the region who paid

00:46:14.990 --> 00:46:19.430
for the net and the region who
didn't pay for the net.

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:25.170
One point before going into the
results of what Cohen, and

00:46:25.170 --> 00:46:31.170
then Pascaline Dupas found for
the bed net is that of course,

00:46:31.170 --> 00:46:34.260
this is not true if it's just
one village and another

00:46:34.260 --> 00:46:36.080
village, like Steve suggested.

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:39.310
Why is it, if we took only one
village, and in one case we

00:46:39.310 --> 00:46:42.640
make free, one case we make not
free-- we can flip a coin,

00:46:42.640 --> 00:46:45.560
and then we compare--

00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:47.200
why is that problematic?

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:47.900
Two villages--

00:46:47.900 --> 00:46:51.516
why is two villages
not enough?

00:46:51.516 --> 00:46:53.262
AUDIENCE: Because you can't make
sure that everything is

00:46:53.262 --> 00:46:56.007
the same [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:56.007 --> 00:46:59.999
like one village might
have more [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:59.999 --> 00:47:03.492
actually care about each other,
or one village might

00:47:03.492 --> 00:47:07.458
end up having a really rainy
season, so all the mosquitoes

00:47:07.458 --> 00:47:09.930
happen to swamp around it.

00:47:09.930 --> 00:47:10.540
ESTHER DUFLO: Exactly.

00:47:10.540 --> 00:47:13.500
Two villages, even if there
is nothing systematically

00:47:13.500 --> 00:47:16.510
different, because you've thrown
a coin, so you didn't

00:47:16.510 --> 00:47:19.730
choose one village rather
than the other for their

00:47:19.730 --> 00:47:22.670
characteristic to give the bed
net for free or to ask people

00:47:22.670 --> 00:47:24.090
to pay for them.

00:47:24.090 --> 00:47:25.860
Even in that case, there are
things that are different

00:47:25.860 --> 00:47:29.170
across villages that you
can't fully control.

00:47:29.170 --> 00:47:32.220
So you need the samples to be
large enough such that all the

00:47:32.220 --> 00:47:35.230
other differences between people
or between regions

00:47:35.230 --> 00:47:39.670
average out, so that even though
you do not observe what

00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:43.910
the demand for bed net would
have been in the free region

00:47:43.910 --> 00:47:46.460
when actually you ask people to
pay for it, you would not

00:47:46.460 --> 00:47:47.340
observe that.

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:51.060
But you can be confident that
what the demand you observe in

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:56.010
the other region where it was
free gives you the right

00:47:56.010 --> 00:47:57.090
counter-factual.

00:47:57.090 --> 00:47:59.580
And for that, the sample needs
to be large enough so that all

00:47:59.580 --> 00:48:02.940
the noise and the idiosyncrasies
get swamped.

00:48:05.740 --> 00:48:10.180
So let's look at two sets
of experiments.

00:48:10.180 --> 00:48:16.210
Both were Pascaline Dupas, who
is a professor at UCLA, was is

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:17.900
involved in both of them.

00:48:17.900 --> 00:48:20.670
The first one was conducted
with Jessica Cohen.

00:48:23.860 --> 00:48:25.330
In and around this
place, which is

00:48:25.330 --> 00:48:27.500
called Busia in Kenya.

00:48:27.500 --> 00:48:30.560
This hotel, you can see that the
beginning of the hotel is

00:48:30.560 --> 00:48:36.440
called "Blue York," where
I spent a lot of time.

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:39.190
And so what did they do?

00:48:39.190 --> 00:48:43.640
They randomly chose clinics,
prenatal clinics, they gave

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:47.070
them nets to give to people who
come for their prenatal

00:48:47.070 --> 00:48:51.770
exam, either at zero or
20 shilling or 30

00:48:51.770 --> 00:48:53.240
shilling or 40 shilling.

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:56.840
So the unit of randomization
is the clinic.

00:48:56.840 --> 00:49:02.150
And then they compare how many
bed nets they sold, and

00:49:02.150 --> 00:49:04.950
whether the bed net got used,
and therefore the effective

00:49:04.950 --> 00:49:07.570
coverage in those clinics.

00:49:07.570 --> 00:49:09.560
And this is what they find.

00:49:09.560 --> 00:49:12.180
So the little vertical
line here is

00:49:12.180 --> 00:49:13.840
the confidence interval.

00:49:13.840 --> 00:49:15.800
So it's taking into account
all the noise that

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:18.010
exists in the data.

00:49:18.010 --> 00:49:21.910
And so what is the conclusion
from this graph, at free, 10

00:49:21.910 --> 00:49:23.390
shilling, 20 shilling,
40 shilling?

00:49:28.570 --> 00:49:34.225
This is the number of nets
sold per week, I think.

00:49:34.225 --> 00:49:37.195
AUDIENCE: Does that indicate if
the customers actually use

00:49:37.195 --> 00:49:38.190
the bed net?

00:49:38.190 --> 00:49:39.410
ESTHER DUFLO: No.

00:49:39.410 --> 00:49:44.840
So far, this is the first look
at, which is just how many bed

00:49:44.840 --> 00:49:47.906
nets were given out.

00:49:47.906 --> 00:49:48.358
Yeah?

00:49:48.358 --> 00:49:49.262
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:49.262 --> 00:49:51.070
the demand curves downward.

00:49:51.070 --> 00:49:52.740
ESTHER DUFLO: The demand curves
downward, and it's

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:54.420
quite steep, right?

00:49:54.420 --> 00:49:56.840
Basically, at 40 shilling,
which is still heavily

00:49:56.840 --> 00:50:02.086
subsidized, because the full
price of a bed net is more

00:50:02.086 --> 00:50:07.680
like 80 shilling, you distribute
only about 10 bed

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:11.310
nets per week, versus 40
per week, when you

00:50:11.310 --> 00:50:13.170
give them for free.

00:50:13.170 --> 00:50:16.580
So it goes down quite steeply.

00:50:16.580 --> 00:50:19.470
And I remember, because they
were randomly selected, we

00:50:19.470 --> 00:50:23.300
know that it is due to the
price, and not due to

00:50:23.300 --> 00:50:24.970
differences across
those regions.

00:50:24.970 --> 00:50:25.463
Yeah?

00:50:25.463 --> 00:50:25.956
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:50:25.956 --> 00:50:29.407
That's funny, because the error
bars are pretty big.

00:50:29.407 --> 00:50:31.379
Like, if you if you looked at
the lower error, versus the

00:50:31.379 --> 00:50:33.850
higher error, it's
[INAUDIBLE].

00:50:33.850 --> 00:50:39.240
ESTHER DUFLO: So you take this
one compared to this one.

00:50:39.240 --> 00:50:41.340
That's the confidence
interval.

00:50:41.340 --> 00:50:45.150
So we are 95% confident that
the truth is somewhere in

00:50:45.150 --> 00:50:46.610
between there.

00:50:46.610 --> 00:50:49.400
That the 95 confidence interval,
[INAUDIBLE].

00:50:52.410 --> 00:50:53.590
Right?

00:50:53.590 --> 00:50:55.535
So you can know that this
is systematically

00:50:55.535 --> 00:50:56.785
different from this.

00:50:59.626 --> 00:51:02.500
You're right that this
and this, the

00:51:02.500 --> 00:51:03.590
confidence interval overlaps.

00:51:03.590 --> 00:51:06.620
And in fact, the numbers
are quite similar.

00:51:06.620 --> 00:51:09.140
This is why I don't answer
someone who was asking why

00:51:09.140 --> 00:51:11.770
didn't I draw the elasticity
that way I'd drawn it that

00:51:11.770 --> 00:51:14.740
way, because I already knew the
answer to the question.

00:51:14.740 --> 00:51:17.290
I was ahead of the
game, slightly.

00:51:17.290 --> 00:51:19.370
So zero to 10 is not such
a big difference.

00:51:19.370 --> 00:51:21.500
Maybe 10 is not that
expensive.

00:51:21.500 --> 00:51:25.315
But 40 is definitely different
from free.

00:51:25.315 --> 00:51:25.970
You're right.

00:51:25.970 --> 00:51:28.060
Certainly we would like those
bars to be smaller.

00:51:28.060 --> 00:51:30.142
If we had more observations,
they would be.

00:51:30.142 --> 00:51:31.910
They would be even
more precise.

00:51:31.910 --> 00:51:32.552
Yes?

00:51:32.552 --> 00:51:35.996
AUDIENCE: Were the clinics far
apart from each other?

00:51:35.996 --> 00:51:39.276
It could be, say, I'd go to the
clinic where I'd have to

00:51:39.276 --> 00:51:40.916
pay 20 shillings [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:44.370 --> 00:51:44.590
ESTHER DUFLO: Right.

00:51:44.590 --> 00:51:45.710
That's a very good point.

00:51:45.710 --> 00:51:48.150
The people shift from one
clinic to the other.

00:51:48.150 --> 00:51:50.020
So they couldn't really do that,
because the clinics were

00:51:50.020 --> 00:51:51.200
quite far away.

00:51:51.200 --> 00:51:53.610
On the other hand, what they did
find is a lot more people

00:51:53.610 --> 00:51:57.430
coming to the clinic, presumably
to get the bed net,

00:51:57.430 --> 00:52:00.680
which is a good thing, because
it cost subsidizes other

00:52:00.680 --> 00:52:02.810
services that you get
in the clinic, in

00:52:02.810 --> 00:52:06.930
particular a test for HIV.

00:52:06.930 --> 00:52:10.350
And if the mother is HIV
positive, then you can give

00:52:10.350 --> 00:52:13.400
them Nevirapine just before the
delivery to prevent the

00:52:13.400 --> 00:52:15.380
transmission to the
[INAUDIBLE].

00:52:15.380 --> 00:52:20.990
So that's another story, which
is a reason why you might want

00:52:20.990 --> 00:52:23.240
to distribute bed nets
if people like them.

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:26.130
Now, this was your question,
which is, but are people are

00:52:26.130 --> 00:52:28.610
using them?

00:52:28.610 --> 00:52:31.680
And so far, the usage, you can
ask people what they tell you.

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:33.085
But they could lie.

00:52:33.085 --> 00:52:35.900
Or you can try and go to their
home and see whether you see

00:52:35.900 --> 00:52:37.050
the bed net.

00:52:37.050 --> 00:52:39.440
And here, what's
the conclusion?

00:52:39.440 --> 00:52:42.670
So this is conditional, having
gotten a bed net.

00:52:42.670 --> 00:52:45.150
So what they did that they
took the register.

00:52:45.150 --> 00:52:48.340
They saw who got a bed net, and
they went to their home

00:52:48.340 --> 00:52:49.940
and said, what are you doing
with the bed net?

00:52:49.940 --> 00:52:53.510
Is it a fishing net or are you
using it for a bed net?

00:52:53.510 --> 00:52:55.382
And what do they find?

00:52:55.382 --> 00:52:58.090
AUDIENCE: What's the y-axis?

00:52:58.090 --> 00:53:01.750
ESTHER DUFLO: So it's percentage
divided by 10.

00:53:01.750 --> 00:53:07.728
So it's 0%, 20%, 40%,
60%, 80%, 100%.

00:53:07.728 --> 00:53:08.724
Ben?

00:53:08.724 --> 00:53:10.716
AUDIENCE: I'm a little confused
about the why.

00:53:10.716 --> 00:53:15.198
So 10 is interesting to me, like
why 50% of the people who

00:53:15.198 --> 00:53:18.200
purchase the bed nets actually
use the bed nets.

00:53:18.200 --> 00:53:19.620
ESTHER DUFLO: So a bit more,
it's more like 60%.

00:53:22.160 --> 00:53:23.440
AUDIENCE: For 10?

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:25.270
ESTHER DUFLO: Yeah,
for 10 shilling.

00:53:25.270 --> 00:53:27.540
It's about 60%.

00:53:27.540 --> 00:53:28.750
AUDIENCE: Can you help
me understand

00:53:28.750 --> 00:53:30.370
why that trend happens?

00:53:30.370 --> 00:53:32.092
ESTHER DUFLO: Oh, why
is it going down?

00:53:32.092 --> 00:53:33.300
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:53:33.300 --> 00:53:33.950
ESTHER DUFLO: It's not--

00:53:33.950 --> 00:53:36.350
I mean, going back to the
question earlier, it's not

00:53:36.350 --> 00:53:37.600
significantly different.

00:53:39.890 --> 00:53:42.000
So it's kind of all similar.

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:46.030
So overall, about the trend,
what do you have to say?

00:53:49.105 --> 00:53:49.955
This is pretty similar.

00:53:49.955 --> 00:53:51.030
It seems pretty flat.

00:53:51.030 --> 00:53:54.870
So there is no very big evidence
that how much of paid

00:53:54.870 --> 00:53:56.936
for a bed net influenced whether
or not you're going to

00:53:56.936 --> 00:53:59.400
use it or not.

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:01.575
And it's not 100%.

00:54:01.575 --> 00:54:04.970
It's more like towards 60%
to 70%, so not everybody

00:54:04.970 --> 00:54:06.760
uses the bed net.

00:54:06.760 --> 00:54:11.580
But how much they pay for it
doesn't affect whether or not

00:54:11.580 --> 00:54:13.150
they use it or not.

00:54:13.150 --> 00:54:16.020
Interestingly, when they went
back six months to a year

00:54:16.020 --> 00:54:18.700
later, more people are
likely to use them.

00:54:18.700 --> 00:54:22.380
So some people just took them
because they were free, maybe,

00:54:22.380 --> 00:54:25.660
or they were not very expensive,
and decided to

00:54:25.660 --> 00:54:28.030
store them for future
usage, which is also

00:54:28.030 --> 00:54:29.630
something you can do.

00:54:29.630 --> 00:54:33.580
So people do not seem to not use
the bed net because they

00:54:33.580 --> 00:54:35.306
got them for free.

00:54:35.306 --> 00:54:37.910
And the result is that if you
look at the effective

00:54:37.910 --> 00:54:41.290
coverage, the effective coverage
is very strongly

00:54:41.290 --> 00:54:44.190
declining with price.

00:54:44.190 --> 00:54:48.630
So the conclusion from their
study is that you should give

00:54:48.630 --> 00:54:51.570
the bed nets for free, because
you get many more bed nets

00:54:51.570 --> 00:54:54.020
out, you're much more
likely to go--

00:54:54.020 --> 00:54:55.600
if you get them for free,
you're going to

00:54:55.600 --> 00:54:58.350
be above 60% coverage.

00:54:58.350 --> 00:55:03.730
And once you go above 60%
coverage, you're more likely

00:55:03.730 --> 00:55:06.000
to buy them.

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:07.770
But before you go, I want
to give you the

00:55:07.770 --> 00:55:11.680
epilogue, which is--

00:55:11.680 --> 00:55:14.390
so this is the reading I asked
you to see, which is people--

00:55:14.390 --> 00:55:18.310
so this got posted on Daniel
Roderick's blog, under the

00:55:18.310 --> 00:55:22.180
title "Jeff Sachs Vindicated,"
which is to say, oh, yeah, we

00:55:22.180 --> 00:55:23.140
should give bed nets for free.

00:55:23.140 --> 00:55:25.120
This experiment showed that.

00:55:25.120 --> 00:55:28.610
And then people complained,
and said, this is only

00:55:28.610 --> 00:55:33.010
pregnant women, and pregnant
women all need the bed net, so

00:55:33.010 --> 00:55:34.860
they are going to use
it at any price.

00:55:34.860 --> 00:55:37.990
The sunk cost effect won't be
there for pregnant women.

00:55:37.990 --> 00:55:41.690
And secondly, it's Kenya, where
bed nets are still quite

00:55:41.690 --> 00:55:43.060
well-known.

00:55:43.060 --> 00:55:52.870
So what are people objecting?

00:55:52.870 --> 00:55:55.740
People are objecting to saying,
the experiment gives

00:55:55.740 --> 00:55:57.460
you a lot of internal
validity.

00:55:57.460 --> 00:56:01.300
We know now that in the specific
context of clinics in

00:56:01.300 --> 00:56:09.050
western Kenya with pregnant
mothers, there is no effect of

00:56:09.050 --> 00:56:11.170
the price you pay on
whether you use.

00:56:11.170 --> 00:56:15.360
But maybe this doesn't apply
to Uganda, Maybe it doesn't

00:56:15.360 --> 00:56:18.490
affect non-pregnant women,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:56:18.490 --> 00:56:21.360
So this is a question of
external validity.

00:56:21.360 --> 00:56:22.610
So what's the solution?

00:56:25.050 --> 00:56:27.440
When these kind of questions
are raised, what's the

00:56:27.440 --> 00:56:31.840
solution to make progress?

00:56:31.840 --> 00:56:33.080
You've can't ignore
these questions.

00:56:33.080 --> 00:56:33.870
They are very good questions.

00:56:33.870 --> 00:56:36.270
What's the solution
to make progress?

00:56:36.270 --> 00:56:36.560
Yes?

00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:38.170
AUDIENCE: Try it
in other areas.

00:56:38.170 --> 00:56:40.130
ESTHER DUFLO: You want to
try it in other areas.

00:56:40.130 --> 00:56:42.630
So in fact, in bed nets,
this got done.

00:56:42.630 --> 00:56:45.740
So this got tried first in
different countries, so in

00:56:45.740 --> 00:56:47.550
Uganda, in Madagascar.

00:56:47.550 --> 00:56:52.830
And secondly, it got tried in
Kenya, but as I was going to

00:56:52.830 --> 00:56:56.810
say, real people, not pregnant
women, but people from the

00:56:56.810 --> 00:56:58.740
market, men and women.

00:56:58.740 --> 00:57:03.070
And here, vouchers got given
at various prices to

00:57:03.070 --> 00:57:09.490
individuals for them to pick
them up in the shop.

00:57:09.490 --> 00:57:13.110
So now this is an environment
where have you would have

00:57:13.110 --> 00:57:17.140
expected to be more likely to
find a sunk cost effect.

00:57:17.140 --> 00:57:20.080
Moreover, the experiment was
also done to look at these

00:57:20.080 --> 00:57:22.470
longer-term consequences.

00:57:22.470 --> 00:57:26.640
So after six months, they went
back again to the same people,

00:57:26.640 --> 00:57:31.960
and tried to sell them a bed net
for 100 shillings, so not

00:57:31.960 --> 00:57:34.700
the lowest price, and not
the highest price.

00:57:34.700 --> 00:57:38.080
And so the question is, the
people who got the first bed

00:57:38.080 --> 00:57:42.290
net for free, are they more
likely to buy the second one

00:57:42.290 --> 00:57:44.670
for 100 shilling, or are they
less likely to buy the second

00:57:44.670 --> 00:57:46.990
one for 100 shilling?

00:57:46.990 --> 00:57:50.160
So I'll run you to the
result quickly.

00:57:50.160 --> 00:57:57.930
So they find the same effect of
price on purchase, that the

00:57:57.930 --> 00:58:01.580
more you pay, the less you
get, quite steeply.

00:58:01.580 --> 00:58:04.430
They find the same lack
of effect of price

00:58:04.430 --> 00:58:05.800
on whether you use.

00:58:05.800 --> 00:58:08.240
And so this is not pregnant
woman anymore.

00:58:08.240 --> 00:58:12.090
So this kind of generalizes
a bit the result.

00:58:12.090 --> 00:58:16.890
And this is the effect on
future approaches, the

00:58:16.890 --> 00:58:19.510
confidence bar, a
little bit high.

00:58:19.510 --> 00:58:23.910
But if anything, what you find
is that people are more likely

00:58:23.910 --> 00:58:29.195
to buy a second bed net when
they got it for free or almost

00:58:29.195 --> 00:58:33.030
free than when they
were offered the

00:58:33.030 --> 00:58:34.940
option to pay for one.

00:58:34.940 --> 00:58:37.470
And this is despite the fact
that at that time, they

00:58:37.470 --> 00:58:39.180
already had a bed net.

00:58:39.180 --> 00:58:42.770
So presumably, their need for
a second bed net is less so.

00:58:42.770 --> 00:58:46.460
So it seems that the learning
effect dominates the

00:58:46.460 --> 00:58:48.220
entitlement effect.

00:58:48.220 --> 00:58:51.210
So if we go back to the
wrecking market story,

00:58:51.210 --> 00:58:55.100
sustainability question you
could say, well actually,

00:58:55.100 --> 00:58:58.580
giving a sweep of bed nets for
free might be a good way to

00:58:58.580 --> 00:58:59.930
create a market.

00:58:59.930 --> 00:59:03.310
Because you create a demand
among people who start

00:59:03.310 --> 00:59:05.390
learning and say, actually,
it's kind of nice,

00:59:05.390 --> 00:59:07.490
that bed nets idea.

00:59:07.490 --> 00:59:10.120
The last way in which you create
a demand is by creating

00:59:10.120 --> 00:59:13.170
this first user of a bed net.

00:59:13.170 --> 00:59:16.490
So this is the last card that
I'm going to show you.

00:59:16.490 --> 00:59:20.260
This is the purchase of a bed
net if you have to pay for it

00:59:20.260 --> 00:59:24.100
if none of your neighbors
got it for free.

00:59:24.100 --> 00:59:29.250
And this is a purchase of a bed
net, if you had to pay for

00:59:29.250 --> 00:59:32.950
it, if all of your neighbors
got it for free.

00:59:32.950 --> 00:59:37.975
And that is randomly assigned,
because depending on who your

00:59:37.975 --> 00:59:40.050
neighbors are, where they are
located, what kind of voucher

00:59:40.050 --> 00:59:43.680
they get, this is just random
whether they get this one.

00:59:43.680 --> 00:59:47.920
And what you see is that if your
neighbor got bed nets for

00:59:47.920 --> 00:59:49.990
free, you're more likely
to get one.

00:59:49.990 --> 00:59:53.470
So there is actually a positive
social effect.

00:59:53.470 --> 00:59:56.830
So the reason why I wanted
detail into this experiment is

00:59:56.830 --> 01:00:01.380
that that's an experiment that
shows us how we can use

01:00:01.380 --> 01:00:04.630
experiments not only to evaluate
the impact of a

01:00:04.630 --> 01:00:07.910
policy, but the answer those
questions that help us

01:00:07.910 --> 01:00:13.530
understand how people decide
whether the entitlement effect

01:00:13.530 --> 01:00:16.580
is bigger or smaller than the
learning effect, whether the

01:00:16.580 --> 01:00:20.460
sunk cost fallacy exists,
whether how the big the price

01:00:20.460 --> 01:00:22.170
elasticities are, et cetera.

01:00:22.170 --> 01:00:24.210
And we need to design
the experiment to

01:00:24.210 --> 01:00:25.720
answer all those questions.

01:00:25.720 --> 01:00:28.820
And then we can start informing
the policy debate.

01:00:28.820 --> 01:00:30.070
Sorry for running over.